The **[Average Fixed Cost][] Curve** is a L-shape curve because the *Fixed Costs* are **fixed** then the AFC **decrease** when the *Quantity of Output* **increase**. This has an important application in the study of [natural monopolies][]. 

The **[Average Variable Cost][] Curve** is a J-shape curve because the *[diminishing marginal product]*. The marginal cost increases with the quantity produced. When a **small amount** is produced, *few workers* are involved, and much of the *equipment is not used*. Because you can easily put these *idle resources to use*, the marginal product of *an additional worker* is **large**, and the marginal cost of *an additional output* is **small**. By contrast, when a **large amount** is produced, the *space is filled with workers*, and most of the *equipment is fully utilized*. It can produce more by*(adding workers*, but these new workers have to work in crowed conditions and may have to wait to use the equipment. Therefore, when the *amount produced is already high*, the marginal product of *an additional worker* is **low**, and the marginal cost of *an extra output* is **large**.

The **[Average Total Cost][] Curve** is a U-shape curve because [Average Fixed Cost][] always declines as output rises because the fixed cost is spread over a larger number of units and [Average Variable Cost][] typically rises as output increases because of [diminishing marginal product][].

The **lowest point of the average total cost** is the most efficient point to perform the production. Sometimes this is called, **[efficient scale][]** because is the quantity of output that minimizes average total cost. The [Marginal Cost][] Curve intersect the [Average Total Cost][] Curve precisely at that point. Whenever [Marginal Cost][] is **less than** [Average Total Cost][], [Average Total Cost][] is **falling**. Whenever [Marginal Cost][] is **greater than** [Average Total Cost][], [Average Total Cost][] is **rising**. At low levels of production, the [Marginal Cost][] is *below* [Average Total Cost][], so [Average Total Cost][] is **falling**. But after the two curves cross, [Marginal Cost][]  increases *above* the [Average Total Cost][]. For the reason just discussed,  [Average Total Cost][] should begin to *rise* to that level of production. Therefore, this point of intersection is
the **minimum average total cost**.


